 00 =================================================================\n==733==ERROR: AddressSanitizer: heap-buffer-overflow on address 0x502000000020 at pc 0x558da9438585 bp 0x7ffd254ac890 sp 0x7ffd254ac880\n=== Length 16 ===\nPROBE: Allocated buffer at 0x502000000010, size=16 bytes\nPROBE: Input string='AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA', strlen=16\nPROBE: Input bytes (hex): 41 41 41 41 41 41 41 41 41 41 41 41 41 41 41 41 00 \n==738==ERROR: AddressSanitizer: heap-buffer-overflow on address 0x502000000020 at pc 0x7f40ef0804bf bp 0x7ffcfd65b900 sp 0x7ffcfd65b0a8\n", "role": "tool", "tool_call_id": "call_00_CKXiNccynkquqoQiStgrUqB6"}], "response": {"id": "f8cd662e-9aaf-422d-8a5f-b47fd269649c", "choices": [{"finish_reason": "tool_calls", "index": 0, "logprobs": null, "message": {"content": "Interesting! Even length 14 and 15 are showing heap-buffer-overflow errors! But the error is different - it says \"heap-buffer-overflow on address 0x502000000020 at pc 0x55adbab03585\" and the stack trace would be different. This looks like ASan is detecting the overflow in a different place (maybe in the free() or something).\n\nActually, looking at the probe output for length 14: the buffer contains 14 'A's (0x41) then null (0x00) then some other byte (0xbe). That's 16 bytes written (0-15). The buffer is 16 bytes (indices 0-15). Writing at index 15 (the null terminator) is within bounds. But ASan might be checking something else.\n\nWait, I think I see the issue! When I print 20 bytes from the buffer with `for (int i = 0; i < 20; i++)`, I'm reading beyond the allocated buffer! That's causing ASan to trigger. Let me fix the probe:", "refusal": null, "role": "assistant", "annotations": null, "audio": null, "function_call": null, "tool_calls": [{"id": "call_00_37ft5EsPWPSyZCHAO55hcerz", "function": {"arguments": "{\"file_path\": \"/src/vuln.c\", \"old_str\": \"    fprintf(stderr, \\\"PROBE: After strcpy, buffer contains: \\\");\\n    for (int i = 0; i < 20; i++) {\\n        fprintf(stderr, \\\"%02x \