"type": "function"}], "content": "Perfect! Now I see the boundary clearly:\n- Length 15 (15 chars + null = 16 bytes): SUCCESS\n- Length 16 (16 chars + null = 17 bytes): CRASH\n- Length 17+: CRASH\n\nThe buffer is 16 bytes, so it can hold strings up to 15 characters plus null terminator. Strings of 16 or more characters will overflow.\n\nBut wait, the variants in the report all crash. variant_4 has \"short\" which is 5 characters. Unless... let me check if maybe the variant files have newlines that are being included. When we use `cat` in command substitution, it preserves newlines. So \"short\\n\" is 6 bytes (5 chars + newline). But that should still fit in 16 bytes.\n\nActually, looking back at the crash reports, all variants show the same pattern: overflow at address `0x502000000020` which is \"0 bytes after 16-byte region\". This is consistent with writing past a 16-byte buffer.\n\nLet me check if maybe the issue is that all test cases are being run in some automated way that always passes the same problematic input. Or perhaps the \"WRITE of size 23\" is ASan reporting something specific.\n\nActually, I think I need to re-examine the code. The buffer is allocated with `malloc(16 * sizeof(char))`. That's 16 bytes. `strcpy` will copy until it finds a null terminator. If the input string is longer than 15 characters (needing 16+ bytes including null), it will overflow.\n\nThe safety property is clear: before calling `strcpy`, we need to ensure `strlen(input) < buffer_size` where `buffer_size = 16`.\n\nBut actually, there's another issue: `strcpy` doesn't know the buffer size. Even if the string fits, `strcpy` will write the null terminator. For a 16-byte buffer, the maximum string length is 15 characters.\n\nLet me add one more probe to check the actual write:"}, {"content": "Successfully edited /src/vuln.c. Snippet around the change:\n    17\t        fprintf(stderr, \"%02x \", (unsigned char)input[i]);\n    18\t    }\n    19\t    fprintf(stderr, \"\\n\");\n    20\